rdt.plugin-key: scribe
rdt.plugin-name: scribe
rdt.plugin-subtitle: Bidirectional sync between a tiddler field (or JSON sub-path) and a state tiddler
rdt.section: Examples
title: $:/plugins/rimir/scribe/doc/examples
type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki

<$transclude $tiddler="$:/plugins/rimir/doc-template/templates/page">
<$fill $name="body">

!! Whole-field text edit

```
<$scribe tiddler="MyNote" field="caption">
  <$edit-text tiddler=<<state>> field="text" tag="input"/>
</$scribe>
```

Typing into the input rewrites `MyNote.caption`. Programmatic changes to `caption` (e.g. another widget setting the field) push the new value back into the input.

!! Pretty-edit a JSON-encoded field

```
<$scribe tiddler="Config" field="profile" type="application/json">
  <$edit-text tiddler=<<state>> field="text" tag="textarea" class="tc-edit-texteditor"/>
</$scribe>
```

The textarea shows pretty-printed JSON. On every keystroke it parses and writes back the compact JSON to `Config.profile`. Invalid JSON falls through unchanged (so it isn't destroyed while the user is mid-typo).

!! Sub-path scalar inside JSON array

This is the pattern the `rimir/kind` plugin's type-builder uses for per-cell editing of field-definitions:

```
<$scribe tiddler=<<type-tid>> field="kind.fields" path=`$(f-idx)$,caption`>
  <$edit-text tiddler=<<state>> field="text" tag="input"/>
</$scribe>
```

The `path` uses backtick-template substitution to interpolate the field index. Editing the input writes back to `kind.fields[<f-idx>].caption`.

!! Sub-path string-array

```
<$scribe tiddler=<<type-tid>> field="kind.fields" path=`$(f-idx)$,constraints` type="application/x-string-array">
  <$edit-text tiddler=<<state>> field="text" tag="input" placeholder="required min:3 unique"/>
</$scribe>
```

State holds a space-separated string. Each keystroke writes a JSON array of trimmed words back to `kind.fields[<f-idx>].constraints`.

!! Date input with smart parser

```
<$scribe tiddler=<<currentTiddler>> field="due-date" type="application/x-tw-date">
  <$edit-text tiddler=<<state>> field="text" tag="input" placeholder="YYYY-MM-DD, today, +7â€¦"/>
</$scribe>
```

State holds `YYYY-MM-DD`. The user can type ISO (`2026-05-21`), German (`21.05.2026`), shortcuts (`today`/`tomorrow`/`yesterday`), or relative offsets (`+7`, `-3d`, `+2w`, `+1m`, `+1y`). On write the value is stored as TW's UTC `YYYYMMDDHHmmsssss` format â€” fully compatible with `<<currentTiddler>>` views, `format:date`, etc. Bad input throws (`<$scribe>` falls through to the previous value).

Datetime variant uses `type="application/x-tw-datetime"` and accepts the same inputs with optional ` HH:mm` suffix. Display becomes `YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm`.

!! Cleanly un-set a property

Clearing the input in either of the sub-path examples above deletes the property entirely from the field def (when the parent is an object). The field-def object survives; just the cleared property is removed.

</$fill>
</$transclude>
